  "prompt": "What is a p type and an n type semiconductor?",
  "response": "P-type and N-type semiconductors are two fundamental types of doped semiconductors used in electronics. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\nN-Type Semiconductor:\n1. Created by adding donor impurities (pentavalent elements) like phosphorus or arsenic to pure semiconductor material\n2. Extra electrons are introduced into the semiconductor's crystal structure\n3. Electrons become the majority charge carriers\n4. Negative charge predominates\n5. Contains excess free electrons\n\nP-Type Semiconductor:\n1. Created by adding acceptor impurities (trivalent elements) like boron or aluminum to pure semiconductor material\n2. \"Holes\" (positive charge carriers) are introduced into the crystal structure\n3. Holes become the majority charge carriers\n4. Positive charge predominates\n5. Contains excess holes\n\nKey Differences:\n- Charge carrier type (electrons vs holes)\n- Impurity type added\n- Electronic behavior\n- Electron concentration\n\nWhen P-type and N-type semiconductors are joined, they form a P-N junction, which is fundamental to many electronic devices like diodes and transistors. This junction allows current to flow in only one direction, making it crucial in electronic applications.\n\nUnderstanding these semiconductor types is essential in electronics and semiconductor device design.",
